      <tr>
        <td bgcolor='dimgray' valign=top width='100' nowrap><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'><b>Ancagalon</b></font></td>
        <td bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top' width='100%'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Well, yesterday I walked into the bank, took out some cash and went to buy some tasty ethnic food in Cabilis (dried froglock legs and lizard milk). "Lock up your daughters residents of Cabilis, dark elf on the prowl." Too sweet. This is is a collection of my findings and reseach. </P><P>As everyone knows, hunting in Howling Stones, Karnor’s Castle and Kaesora hurt Venril Sathir faction. Hunting in any of these zones for long will pretty much ensure you will lose the ability to bank in the Overthere Outpost. I know for myself, the idea of losing the only bank on the continent is not appealing. The options to raise faction are for Firona Vie and Cabilis, with Cabilis being the superior city. It is centrally located on Kunark, and much more accessable then Firona, as well it has a necromancer guild. So this is my document on how to raise faction in Cabilis for a Dark Elf worshipping Innoruuk. </P><P>First off, these are my findings on the basics of faction. Faction values:</P><P>Scowling	-801 and lower<BR>Threatening	-800 to -501<BR>Dubious		-500 to -101<BR>Apprehensive 	-100 to -1<BR>Indifferent	0 to 100<BR>Amiable		101 to 500<BR>Kindly		501 to 800<BR>Warmly		801 and higher</P><P>Scowling and Threatening will attack you on site. Dubious will allow you to walk past and not get attacked, but the merchants will still not deal with you. Apprehensive is the lowest category that you can be in for the merchants to open a trade window. Strangely enough, even if you are Scowling with a banker, you can still open a trade window, but the banker will attack you a few seconds afterwards. To get around this, you can make use of Feign Death right near a banker and then open a trade window, but since banks are usually crawling with guards, this can be risky at best. There are some other important notes about faction. First, there was a patch so that merchants in any town will at worse con dubious, even if your faction score puts you into a lower category. This was done so that merchants will never attack, unless you hit them first. Second, there was a patch recently changing the way factions were awarded. Before, if you did something that gave multiple faction adjustments, and you were at a maximum / minimum with one of the factions, you did not get any faction adjustments. So if you were maxed with one faction, and you needed to do a quest, you would need to lower faction with the maxed faction in order to get any faction changes from the quest. This has been changed so that you will receive faction adjustments for any factions that are not maxed. Third, most creatures you kill or quests you complete give one faction point. There are many creatures and quests which have heavier faction adjustments. The best example is probably in Kael Drakkal, where killing the perimeter guards will give you minor faction hits, while moving deeper in the city to kill officers will give you heavier faction hits, and killing royalty will suffer you massive hits to your giant faction.  </P><P>So on to Cablilis. First, these are the different faction groups in Cabilis and my calculation as to where a Dark Elf worshipping Innoruuk starts.</P><P>-1000 	Legion of Cabilis (most Troopers)<BR>-1450	Swiftails	(monk guild and Crusader Quag)<BR>-1550	Crusaders of Greenmist (most Crusaders)<BR>-1500 	Brood of Kotiz (Necromancer guild and most merchants in West Cabilis)<BR>-1500	Scaled Mystics (Shaman guild)<BR>-2500	Cabilis Residents (bankers, most merchants in East Cabilis, Jozter, Frizazz and several NPCs in the Haggle Barron building)</P><P>It should be noted that these seem to be the starting values for non-iskar who worship an “evil” god that is not Cazic Thule. Angostics and Worshippers of Cazic Thule get huge bonuses to their starting factions (or they are not awarded the same penalties we are). I have yet to read a post about Cabilis starting faction for players worshipping a “good” god. I would imagine there is no motivation to get into Cabilis with the ability to bank in Firona Vie.</P><P>The first thing to do is to raise your Legion faction so you can get access to the various quests you can do to raise the other factions. You have 2 options to raise Legion faction. Killing goblins or Sarnak in the zones adjacent to Cabilis will raise your faction with the Legion. Killing the Foresaken (which include Iskar Bandits / Marauders / Manslayers) in the zones adjacent to Cabilis will raise faction with both Legion and Brood. Killing  Foresaken is the only way to raise brood faction. So, it is probably better to stick to killing Foresaken, as you are killing 2 birds with one stone, even though there are a lot less Foresaken then there are goblins running around. Field of Bone and the Warsilk Woods are probably the best areas to kill the Foresaken. Your first goal is to get up to Dubious with the Troopers, so that means you will need to kill 500 Foresaken.</P><P>Once you are at Dubious with the Troopers the real pain begins. There are several low-level quests that give faction. The Bone Chip Quest, Scorpion Pincer Quest, Watcher Torch Quest and Hatchling Brain Quest which all give one faction point for Legion, Swiftail, Crusader, Mystic and Resident factions. The Curscale Armor Quest gives faction for Legion and Resident, and it appears to give more then one point per quest. </P><P>The bone chip quest is the popular choice to raise faction, as bone chips are available in many zones, and because they stack, saving traveling time. Trooper Mozo at the gates to the Field of Bone is who you need to turn the chips into. Stand as close to the wall and hand him 4 stacks of 4 chips (quite a time saver). There are 2 Crusaders (Quag and Boli) who patrol the area, so make sure you are aware of them until you get to Dubious. I never had any problems with them, but some people have agroed them, which is a bad thing. They are level 50, Harm Touch for about 750, hit for 250 and have about 32K HPs. Nasty stuff. Also important to note is that Crusader Quag appears to be on Swiftail faction and not Crusader faction, so when you are testing your standing with the Crusaders, use Crusader Boli. After you are Apprehensive with the Residents, go back and kill some more Foresaken to finish up your faction with the Brood. </P><P>So there you have it. Kill 1400 Foresaken, hand in 9600 bone chips (480 stacks) and you will be able to bank, buy /sell to any merchant, be welcome in any guild hall and not have to worry about being killed by anything in Cabilis (well except those Froglock Slaves, who will attack you if you sit near them). </P><P>So how does one gather 480 stacks of bone chips? The best zones in the game for auctioning for bone chips are probably Field of Bone, Kurn’s Tower, Greater Faydark, Nektulos and Paneel. I set up mules in all of these zones, and would rotate between them auctioning for chips. I chose to offer 4pp per stack and more for people selling large quantities of chips at one time. This can be costly, but much faster then offering 2pp per stack. </P><P>Probably the best place to harvest bone chips yourself is in the newbie area in Paneel. There are 2 areas that spawn decaying skeletons. Killing all the decaying skeletons on a spawn point will cause the point to respawn almost instantly. Set up a hot-button “/pet attack decay” and hammer it repeatedly. It is amazing how many decaying skeletons you can drop in a short period of time. The real time sink here is picking up the chips. I found it most expedient to get a newbie to team up with me. I just ran around hammering my pet hot-key while they picked up the chips and discarded the rusty weapons. Then I would buy the chips back from them at a pre-set price. It would be best to get a partner who can SOW you and your pet, but druids and shammies are rare in that part of the world. With a partner, you can get 5 packs of chips in under 3 hours. Bind in Paneel, gather 5 packs of chips, use the Overthere Hammer to get back to Kunark, run to Trooper Mozo, turn in chips and gate back to Paneel. 12 trips like this and you have it made. </P><P>As an aside to this, I have really started to notice a trend in gathering bone chips. It is really apparent that there are less and less “true newbies” in the game. Greater Faydark is probably the most heavily trafficked area for starting characters. When I was there auctioning for bone chips for 4pp (which should be very good money for characters level 1 to 10), but I found surprisingly few people selling chips. I found this same situation in the Field of Bone and Kurn’s Tower. I made a point of watching a bit closer and found that a majority of the lower-levels are quite obviously twinks. Several times when I was auctioning for chips, I would have competition from another character who was level 1, auctioning to buy bone chips for 5pp per stack. When I asked them what the bone chips were for, they always replied that they were to use the various bone chip quests to power-level themselves. Just a small observation that definitely might impact anyone who is looking to buy chips in these quantities. </P><P>Cheers,<BR>Ancagalon the Black</P><P> </font></td>
